{{Other uses|Crepe (disambiguation)}} [[File:Woman's Bonnet (Mourning) LACMA 41.11.8.jpg|thumb|Woman's mourning bonnet in hard crape, c.1880]] '''Crêpe''', also spelt '''crepe''' or '''crape''' (from the [[French language|Fr.]] ''crêpe''<ref>[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?search=crepe&searchmode=none Online Etymology Dictionary]</ref>), is a [[silk]], [[wool]], or [[synthetic fiber]] [[Textile|fabric]] with a distinctively crisp, crimped appearance. The term ''crape'' typically refers to a form of the fabric associated specifically with [[mourning]].<ref name=dic>[http://dictionary.reference.com/browse/crape Dictionary.com]</ref> Crêpe is also historically called ''crespe'' or ''crisp''.<ref name=lou>Taylor, pp. 246-253</ref>
==Types==
===Types (A to C)=== [[File:Woman's Ball Gown LACMA M.2007.211.939 (2 of 3).jpg|thumb|right|Detail of an aerophane dress, c.1827]] * '''Aerophane''': # Crimped silk [[gauze]] with a crêpe texture. # A historic 19th century lightweight crêpe,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA6 Tortora & Johnson], p. 6</ref> introduced in 1820,<ref name=lew6>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gbIsJ2tZJS4C&pg=PA6 Lewandowski], p.6</ref> and, as ''crepe aerophane'' in 1861.<ref name=lewcrepe/> * '''Albert crêpe''': # A superior-quality black silk mourning crêpe used since 1862.<ref name=lew6/> # Plain-weave crêpe. # An English-made silk and cotton blend crêpe.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA10#v=onepage&q&f=false Tortora & Johnson], p.10</ref> * '''Alicienne''': A furnishing fabric with alternating plain weave and crêpe stripes.<ref name=fc2/> * '''Alpaca crêpe''': Rayon and acetate blend crêpe with a woollen texture, not necessarily made of [[alpaca]] yarn.<ref name=fc2>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA14 Tortora & Johnson], p. 14</ref> * '''Altesse''': A British plain-weave silk fabric with crêpe filling.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA14 Tortora & Johnson], p.14</ref> * '''Arabian''': # A British-made plain-weave cloth with figured crêpe designs # Piece-dyed silk crêpe embroidered with dots.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA23 Tortora & Johnson], p. 23</ref> * '''Armure''' See ''Georgian crêpe''. * '''Balanced crêpe''': Crêpe woven with alternating S and Z twist yarns in both directions.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA39 Tortora & Johnson], p.39</ref> * '''Balmoral crape''': An 1895 English crape.<ref name=lewba>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gbIsJ2tZJS4C&pg=PA22 Lewandowski], p. 22</ref> * '''Balzerine''': An 1889 narrow-striped silk [[Grenadine (cloth)|grenadine]] overlaid with wider crêpe stripes. An earlier 1830s cotton/worsted fabric, spelled balzarine, is probably not crêpe.<ref name=lewba/> * '''Bark (or tree-bark) crêpe''': A broad term describing rough crêpes with a [[bark (botany)|bark]] texture.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gbIsJ2tZJS4C&pg=PA25 Lewandowski], p. 25</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA45 Tortora & Johnson], p.45</ref> * '''Bauté satin''': Warp-woven satin with a plain crêpe reverse.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA52 Tortora & Johnson], p. 52</ref> * '''Borada crape''': A cheaper, economical version of mourning crape advertised in c.1887.<ref name=lou/> * '''Bologna crêpe''': Silk crêpe used for mourning, also known as valle cypre.<ref>Tortora & Johnson, p. 66</ref> * '''Canton crêpe''': A soft silk crêpe with a pebbly surface originally associated with [[Guangdong|Canton]] in China, with bias ribs. Made in Britain, but exported to China, hence its name.<ref>Tortora & Johnson, p. 96</ref> * '''Caustic soda crêpe''': Cotton treated with chemicals to create a crêpe-like texture, often in patterns.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA107 Tortora & Johnson], p. 52</ref> * '''Chiffon crêpe''': [[Chiffon (fabric)|Chiffon]]-weight crêpe.<ref name=lew1>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gbIsJ2tZJS4C&pg=PA62 Lewandowski], p. 52</ref> * '''Chijimi''': Japanese crêpe.<ref name=lew1/> [[File:Chirimen (Japanese crepe) of rayon.jpg|right|thumb|Chirimen]] * '''Chirimen''': Japanese raw silk crêpe widely used for kimonos.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=KsN81J1s70kC&pg=PA276 Ikegami], p.276</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gYNGAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA92 Panda], p.92</ref> When woven with a dot it is ''mon-chirimen''.<ref name=lewm/> *'''Courtauld crape''': 1890s mourning crape made by [[Courtaulds]]. An 1894 variation, called ''Courtauld's new silk crêpe'', was exceptionally thin and soft.<ref name=lewcrepe/> Courtaulds monopolised the export market for English crapes and crêpes, meaning that the textiles known as ''crape anglaise'' were almost always manufactured by Courtaulds up until 1940.<ref name=lou/> * '''Crêpe Algerian''': A trade name for a printed [[pongee]] with a rough crêpe texture.<ref name=fc3>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA156 Tortora & Johnson], p. 156</ref> * '''Crêpe anglaise''': A French term for English mourning crapes in black and white.<ref name=lewcrepe>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gbIsJ2tZJS4C&pg=PA77 Lewandowski], p.77</ref> The only true 'crape anglais' was considered that made by Courtaulds (see ''Courtauld crape'') which was last made in 1940.<ref name=lou/> * '''Crêpe Beatrice''': Trade name for crêpe with a light warp stripe.<ref name=fc3/> * '''Crêpe berber''': Trade name for a piece-dyed crepe-textured pongee.<ref name=fc4>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA157 Tortora & Johnson], p. 157</ref> *'''Crêpe [[charmeuse]]''': Lightweight silk satin with a [[Grenadine (cloth)|grenadine]] warp and crêpe reverse.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe chenette''': A tradename for a strong crêpe with a pebble texture.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe crêpe''': Made with extra twists in the warp to create an extra-deep texture.<ref name=fc4/> [[File:Till boken - utställningen Kunglig Vintage - Livrustkammaren - 87606.tif|thumb|Crepe de chine]] * '''Crêpe de chine''': A fine, lightweight silk, cotton, or worsted, with a plain weave and crêpe-twist filling.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe de chine travers''': A ribbed crêpe de chine with heavier filling yarns introduced to the weave at regular intervals.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe de dante''': Crêpe with silk and wool filling.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe de lahor''': Cotton crêpe made in France.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe de laine''': A sheer wool fabric plain-woven with hard twist for a slight crêpe effect.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe de santé''': An undyed, closely woven, rough-textured wool-blend crêpe mixed with silk, linen or cotton, also called "health crepe"<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe de Suisse''': 1860 dress fabric.<ref name=lewcrepe/> * '''Crêpe d'espagne''': Open-weave fabric with a silk warp and wool filling.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe diana''': Trade name for a cotton and silk blend crêpe.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe Elizabeth''': English term for a mottled or pebbled [[georgette (fabric)|georgette]].<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe faille sublime''': Silk [[grosgrain]] with a hard-twist filling.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe flannel''': Plain-woven worsted with a crêpe finish.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe imperial''' Late 19th century woollen crape.<ref name=lewcrepe/> * '''Crêpe jacquard''': Crepe with designs produced by [[jacquard weaving]].<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe janigor''': Trade name for a heavy rib textile with alternating rayon and dull acetate warp threads, cross-dyed for varied shades.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe jersey''': Vertically ribbed silk crêpe resembling the [[jersey (fabric)|knit fabric]].<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe lissé (or lease)''': A lightweight, lustrous, slightly stiffened open-weave silk or cotton crêpe, with fewer twists than a ''crêpe crêpe''.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpela''': French term for a crêpe effect.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crepeline''': Very sheer plain-woven silk usually used in textile conservation.<ref name=fc4/> Originally introduced in the 1870s as a cheap alternative to crepe de chine.<ref name=lewcrepe/> * '''Crêpella''': Plain-woven worsted using hard-spun yarn.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe maretz''' An 1862 fabric.<ref name=lewcrepe/> * '''Crêpe marocain''': Heavy, cross-ribbed crêpe where the filling yarn is coarser than the warp, resembling a canton crêpe.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe meteor''': Soft silk crêpe, [[twill]] weave reversing to satin.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe mohair''': Silk and [[mohair]] blend crêpe.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe morette''': Trade name. Lightweight worsted crêpe with heavier, looser filling.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe mosseux''': A type of opaque [[voile]] which resists shrinkage.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe myosotis''' A later mourning crêpe made in the 1930s, in crimped silk with a soft finish.<ref name=lewcrepe/> Courtaulds launched this textile in the early 1930s as an alternative to the increasingly unpopular traditional stiff mourning crapes.<ref name=lou/> * '''Crepenette''': Crêpe-effect pongee.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe ondese''': Rough textured rayon-acetate blend crêpe.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe poplin''': A late 19th century silk-wool rib fabric with crêpe effect.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe rachel''': French print cotton-worsted blend crêpe.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe radio''': British raw silk crêpe with a ribbed effect, using alternate double rows of S-twist and Z-twist.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crêpe royal''': Sheer crêpe-de-chine introduced in 1889.<ref name=lewcrepe/> * '''Crêpe suzette''': A variation on crepon georgette.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crepine''': Silk with crêpe dots. The name also describes a type of [[fringe (trim)|fringe]].<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crepoline''': A class of transparent fabrics with a warp-wise crêpe effect.<ref name=fc4/> * '''Crepon''': A heavier crêpe with an exaggerated warp-directional texture produced by several weaving techniques.<ref name=fc4/> A soft silky version was introduced in 1866, and the second, much heavier version in 1882. In the 1890s crepon also described a woollen fabric that puffed between stripes or squares, including crepon milleraye (striped) and crepon Persian (with 'Oriental patterns').<ref name=lewcrepe/> * '''Crystal crêpe''': An English term for silk crêpe.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA164 Tortora & Johnson], p. 164</ref> * '''Crespe''': Lightweight crimped mourning gauze, late 16th century.<ref name=lewcrepe/> * '''Cynara''': An crêpe-type fabric in rayon and acetate.<ref>Tortora & Johnson, p. 168</ref> * '''Cyprus''': Fine crêpe used for mourning hatbands in the 15th-17th centuries, made in Cyprus.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gbIsJ2tZJS4C&pg=PA81 Lewandowski], p. 81</ref>
===Types (E to L)=== *''' 'ele'ele kanikau''': Black mourning crêpe worn in Hawaii.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gbIsJ2tZJS4C&pg=PA96 Lewandowski], p. 96</ref> * '''Epingline''': Textile in silk, rayon or worsted with a crêpe surface.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gbIsJ2tZJS4C&pg=PA99 Lewandowski], p. 99</ref> * '''Esmeralda''' or '''étendelle''': Sheer white crêpe or gauze popular in the early 19th century, often embroidered.<ref>Tortora & Johnson, p. 215</ref> * '''Flat crêpe''': Also called mock crepe or (inaccurately) French crepe. A smooth, flat plain-weave fabric, typically a silk blend, with hard-twisted yarns and ordinary yarn warp. Also used to describe a similar fabric made without crepe-twist yarns.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA236 Tortora & Johnson], p. 236</ref> * '''French crêpe''': Inaccurately applied to ''flat crêpe''. # Plain-weave light silk or rayon cloths similar to flat crêpe. # A lingerie weight fabric with ordinary yarn warp and a twisted filling yarn that is less twisted than typical crepe twist.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA247 Tortora & Johnson], p. 247</ref> * '''Gamsa''': An imitation satin-backed crêpe in twill weave rayon.<ref>Tortora & Johnson, p. 254</ref> [[File:KLÄNNING Syrenlila sidenklänning med cape och underklänning. Tillhört Ebba von Eckermann, f - Hallwylska museet - 89129.tif|thumb|upright|Georgette evening dress, 1930s]] * '''[[Georgette (fabric)|Georgette]]''': Sheer, lightweight fabric named after the couturiere Georgette de la Plante.<ref name=mbp>{{cite book|last=Picken|first=Mary Brooks|title=A Dictionary of Costume and Fashion: Historic and Modern|year=1957|publisher=Courier Corporation|isbn=9780486402949|pages=88|authorlink=Mary Brooks Picken}}</ref> # A crepe-surfaced plain weave silk or synthetic fabric with alternating S and Z twist yarns in both warp and weft. # An English term for cotton crepe.<ref name=fc5>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA259 Tortora & Johnson], p. 259</ref> * '''Georgian crêpe''': A chain-pebbled crêpe (called ''armure'' in France) often with diamond, shield or bird's-eye motifs.<ref name=fc5/> * '''Health crêpe''': See ''crêpe de santé''. * '''Lingerie crêpe''': See ''French crêpe''.
===Types (M to Y)=== * '''Marana''': Woollen crepe, very resilient and drapable.<ref>Tortora & Johnson, p. 372</ref> * '''Mock crêpe''': See ''flat crêpe'' * '''Momie crêpe''': Light cotton fabric.<ref name=lewm>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gbIsJ2tZJS4C&pg=PA194 Lewandowski], p. 194</ref> * '''Moss crepe''': See ''sand crepe'' * '''Norwich crêpe or crape''': # 19th century silk warp and worsted, resembling a non-twill [[bombazine]] but not considered true crêpe. # 17th century black-dyed worsted crêpe made in England. # A georgette-like silk and cotton blend fabric in a crêpe weave.<ref name=lou/><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA418 Tortora & Johnson], p. 418</ref> * '''Pekin crêpe''': Pekin (shiny and matte striped textile) woven with a crêpe weft.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gbIsJ2tZJS4C&pg=PA224 Lewandowski], p. 224</ref> * '''Plissé''': Mainly cotton fabric with a crêpe effect created by chemically treating the fabric to pucker and crinkle, typically in stripes. Plissé satin is made using crêpe yarns.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA465 Tortora & Johnson], p. 465</ref> * '''Reverse crêpe''': Woven with a crêpe yarn warp and flat filling.<ref>Tortora & Johnson, p. 509</ref> * '''Rhythm crêpe''': Plain-weave rayon with [[seersucker]] stripe.<ref>Tortora & Johnson, p. 510</ref> * '''Romaine''': Heavy but transparent crêpe.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gbIsJ2tZJS4C&pg=PA252 Lewandowski], p. 252</ref> * '''Roshanara''': Trade name for heavily ribbed satin-backed crepe.<ref>Tortora & Johnson, p. 517</ref> * '''Russian crêpe''': Invented in 1881. A coarse-weave crêpe.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=gbIsJ2tZJS4C&pg=PA254 Lewandowski], p. 254</ref> * '''Sand crepe''' or '''moss crepe''': Crêpe with a grained or frosted surface appearance, created with a small [[dobby (cloth)|dobby weave]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=LTYfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA527 Tortora & Johnson], p. 527</ref> * '''Sawdust crêpe''': Similar to ''sand crêpe'' but with a harsher surface.<ref>Tortora & Johnson, p. 536</ref> * '''Satin-back crêpe''': Reversible fabric with a [[satin]] face and a crêpe reverse.<ref name=fc3/> * '''Shioze''': Japanese spun-silk crêpe.<ref>Tortora & Johnson, p. 555</ref> * '''Spanish crêpe''': See ''d'espagne''. * '''Victoria crepe''': British-made cotton crêpe with a high lustre.<ref>Tortora & Johnson, p. 664</ref> * '''Yantsou''': Figured silk crêpe made in [[Yantai]], Eastern China.<ref>Tortora & Johnson, p. 693</ref> * '''Yeddo crêpe''': Soft cotton fabric, medium weight.<ref>Tortora & Johnson, p. 695</ref>
